&gt; non-native writers want to be told to spell as they
&gt; guess or imagine that a word should be pronounced in
&gt; the accent of English which they aim to speak. That
&gt; would be te reintroduce the some trouble we have with
&gt; TO by the back door.
&gt;








A non-native speaker learning English will use books designed for that 
purpose.  Once the content is digital, it will probably become quite 
simple for the spelling in that primer to be altered automatically to 
match the accent that the student wants to learn.  And once there are 
newspapers, magazines etc. available in QS, as the student reads them, 
the spelling in them will begin to make sense to the student and will 
indicate the pronunciation to him.  He will not be in the situation of 
&quot;guessing&quot; how a word should be pronounced.  He will be led down a 
structured path toward relative English fluency.

This is quite different from telling people who are already fluent 
English speakers that they must memorize how words should be spelt in 
QS.  An alphabet is simply a code for getting the sounds of a language 
down on paper or an electronic screen to transmit information to 
others.  If the code is not closely related to the way people actually 
speak, then we are setting ourselves up for failure in my estimation.

Paige

